Encoding:  transforms data into another format using a scheme that is publicly available so that
it can easily be reversed.
It does not require a key as the only thing required to decode it is the algorithm that was used to encode it.
Examples: ASCII, Unicode, URL Encoding, Base64, UTF-8

- It's not for security.
-

Encryption: The purpose of encryption is to transform data in order to keep it secret from others.

Encryption hide information, only someone with proper key can recover it.
                        Plain Text
                        ↓
                        Encryption
                        ↓
                        Cipher Text
                        ↓
                        Decryption
                        ↓
                        Plain Text

Algorithms:
1- Symmetric Encryption: Using the same key for encryption and decryption
    AES (standard today)
    DES (obsolete)
    3DES (legacy)
    ChaCha20
2- Asymmetric Encryption: 2 keys
                Public Key
                ↓
                Encrypt
                ↓
                Private Key
                ↓
                Decrypt

  RSA
  ECC (Elliptic Curve Cryptography)

used in HTTPS key exchange, SSH, Email Encryption using tls.

